      explanation: 'Cognitive dissonance (Festinger, 1957): holding two psychologically inconsistent cognitions ("I paid a lot for this car" and "this car is unreliable") produces aversive psychological arousal (dissonance). People are motivated to reduce dissonance by: (1) changing a cognition, (2) adding new reconciling cognitions, or (3) minimizing the importance of one cognition. The buyer cannot un-purchase the car, so they minimize the negative cognition (dismissing reliability issues) and amplify positive cognitions — classic post-decision dissonance reduction.',
